{"title_page": "Jamie Lloyd", "text_new": "{{For|the British theater director|Jamie Lloyd (director)}}\n{{In-universe|subject = film|category = film|date = December 2010}}\n\n{{Infobox character\n|series        = [[Halloween (franchise)|Halloween]]\n|image         = Jamie Lloyd.jpg\n|image_size    = 250px\n|caption       = [[Danielle Harris]] as Jamie Lloyd in the fourth film\n|creator       = [[Alan B. McElroy]]\n|portrayer     = [[Danielle Harris]] (''Halloween [[Halloween 4: The Return of Michael Myers|4]]'' & ''[[Halloween 5: The Revenge of Michael Myers|5]]'') <br>[[J. C. Brandy]] (''Halloween [[Halloween: The Curse of Michael Myers|6]]'')\n|first          = ''[[Halloween 4: The Return of Michael Myers]]''\n|last           = ''[[Halloween: The Curse of Michael Myers]]''\n|family        = [[Laurie Strode]] (deceased mother) \n|children      = Stephen Lloyd (son/cousin in Producer's Cut; orphaned)\n|relatives     = [[List of Halloween (franchise) characters#Judith Myers|Judith Myers]] (deceased maternal aunt) <br>[[Michael Myers (Halloween)|Michael Myers]] (maternal uncle) <br> Morgan Strode (deceased maternal grandfather) <br> Pamela Strode (deceased maternal grandmother) <br> Richard Carruthers (foster father) <br> Darlene Carruthers (foster mother) <br> Rachel Carruthers (deceased foster sister) <br> John Strode (deceased maternal great-uncle) <br> Debra Strode (deceased maternal great-aunt) <br> Tim Strode (deceased maternal first cousin once removed) <br> Kara Strode (maternal first cousin once removed) <br> Danny Strode (maternal second cousin)\n}}\n'''Jamie Lloyd''' is a [[character (arts)|fictional character]] in the [[Halloween (franchise)|''Halloween'' franchise]] and the main [[protagonist]] of ''[[Halloween 4: The Return of Michael Myers|Halloween 4]]'' and ''[[Halloween 5: The Revenge of Michael Myers|5]]'' and also appears  in a less prominent role in ''[[Halloween: The Curse of Michael Myers]]''. The character was created by [[Alan B. McElroy]] and portrayed by actress [[Danielle Harris]] in the fourth and fifth films of the series, while [[J.C. Brandy]] portrays her in the sixth.\n\nThe character was created after [[Jamie Lee Curtis]] declined to return as [[Laurie Strode]] for the fourth film due to not wanting to continue her participation in the film. As a result, her character was written out and died in a car accident, which is briefly explained in the film. Originally, the character was named Brittany \"Britti\" Lloyd. Britti's name was later changed to Jamie, a homage to Laurie Strode actress [[Jamie Lee Curtis]]. The fourth film introduced Laurie's daughter, Jamie Lloyd. As the daughter of Laurie, she is also the niece of infamous [[serial killer]] [[Michael Myers (Halloween)|Michael Myers]] and his first victim, [[List of Halloween (franchise) characters#Judith Myers|Judith Myers]].\n\n==Appearances==\n===Films===\nFirst appearing in ''[[Halloween 4: The Return of Michael Myers]]'' (1988), Jamie is [[Laurie Strode]]'s daughter, as well as the niece of [[#Judith Myers|Judith]] and [[Michael Myers (Halloween)|Michael Myers]], which she and all of Haddonfield know about. Her father is unknown since her surname was never explained or elaborated in films where it came from when she appeared. She is put in the care of a foster family, the Carruthers, and later [[adoption|adopted]] after Laurie dies in a car crash. She suffers from nightmares about Michael and is bullied at school for being related to \"The Boogeyman\". On October 30, 1988, Michael is being transferred out of Ridgemont Federal Sanitarium back to Smith's Grove. While in the transfer ambulance, he recovers from his ten-year coma upon learning the existence of his niece. Accordingly, he kills the two medical attendants and the two drivers. While making his way back to his hometown, he also kills a mechanic and a waitress. In Haddonfield, while on the trail for Jamie, Michael kills the Carruthers' Golden Retriever Sundae, a worker at the power plant which causes a blackout of the entire town, the entire police force, the deputy, the police chief's daughter Kelly, Rachel's boyfriend Brady, and 4 men from a vigilante mob. Escaping from town, Jamie cowers in a pick-up truck as Rachel hits Michael head on, throwing him off the road and knocking him out. Despite Rachel's orders, Jamie goes over to him and holds his hand. The police tell Jamie to drop to the ground and shoot Michael many times, causing him to fall into an abandoned mine shaft, which then collapses on top of him. Later, back in her foster home, Jamie is possessed by Michael's spirit and attacks her foster mother. When screams are heard from upstairs, Dr. Loomis walks over to the staircase seeing Jamie poised at the top holding a pair of bloody scissors, similar to Michael when he killed his older sister Judith. Sheriff Ben Meeker (Beau Starr) restrains Loomis from shooting her, and both men, Mr. Carruthers, and Rachel watch in horror, realizing that Jamie is following in Michael's footsteps. ''[[Halloween 5: The Revenge of Michael Myers]]'' (1989), taking place a year later, has a severely traumatized Jamie housed in the Haddonfield Children's Clinic. She has now been rendered mute and suffers from nightmares and seizures, and being treated for attacking her foster mother under Michael's influence, though her foster mother survived. Early in the film, a brick, bearing a note reading, \"The evil child must die,\" is thrown through her window.  When Michael ([[Donald L. Shanks]]) awakens from a year-long coma, she exhibits signs of a [[Telepathy|telepathic]] link with her uncle, eventually regains the ability to speak, and has seizures whenever her uncle kills someone. Michael kills Rachel, four of Rachel's friends, two cops, and the Carruthers' new dog, a Doberman Pinscher named Max, while in pursuit of Jamie. Towards the end, Loomis takes Jamie to the old Myers house and successfully lures Michael into the house by having Jamie reenact her aunt Judith's final moments. Despite the doctor's pleas with Michael to fight his rage and seek redemption through a positive relationship with Jamie, Myers tracks down his niece in Judith Myers' deserted bedroom. Michael finds Jamie, but before he can kill her, she tries to appeal to her uncle's humanity. At Jamie's request, Michael takes off his mask. However, Jamie touches Michael's face, sending him into a fit of rage. Using Jamie as bait, Loomis catches Michael in a net, shoots him with tranquilizer darts, and beats him unconscious with a wooden beam. Michael is manacled and locked up in the local jail, awaiting transport to a maximum-security facility, where, Meeker says, he will remain \"until the day he dies,\" to which Jamie responds, \"He'll never die.\" After Jamie is escorted out to be taken home, a mysterious \"Man in Black\" arrives and attacks the police station. Jamie goes back inside to find that eight police officers have been gunned down, including Meeker, and that her uncle has escaped, prompting her to begin sobbing in terror. In ''[[Halloween: The Curse of Michael Myers]]'' (1995), the Man in Black kidnaps Jamie immediately after the shoot-out and has kept her and Michael ([[George P. Wilbur]]) in captivity for the past six years. 15-year-old Jamie gives birth to a boy on the night of October 30, 1995. [[Samuel Loomis|Dr. Loomis]] and Tommy Doyle ([[Paul Rudd]]), whom Laurie Strode was babysitting on Halloween 1978, attempt to rescue Jamie after hearing her plea for help on a local radio station. Michael kills Jamie by impaling her on a corn [[threshing machine|thresher]] and turning it on, disemboweling her. Before being killed, Jamie hides her [[infant]], who is found by Tommy. The Man in Black is revealed to be Loomis' former medical colleague [[List of Halloween (franchise) characters#Dr. Terence Wynn|Dr. Terence Wynn]] ([[Mitchell Ryan]]). He and most of his staff are revealed to be a [[Druid]] cult headquartered in the subterranean levels of the Smith's Grove Sanitarium, the place where Michael was committed after killing his sister Judith. They are responsible for Michael's actions, placing an ancient curse on him to kill his family to ward off sickness and death. By the end of the movie, it is implied that Dr. Wynn has been trying and failing to breed the ultimate evil using Michael's DNA and female patients of the sanitarium in [[in vitro fertilisation|in-vitro fertilization]] experiments; finally reaching a success with Jamie's baby after she had been tested on. In the original cut of the film, Jamie does not die at the beginning of the film, and instead survives a knife attack by Michael in the barn. She remains in a [[coma]] and is taken to the hospital, where Loomis and Wynn visit her. Later, an unseen person, later revealed to be Wynn, shoots the unconscious Jamie in the head with a silenced pistol.\n\nWhen screenwriter [[Kevin Williamson (screenwriter)|Kevin Williamson]] first outlined ''[[Halloween H20: 20 Years Later]]'' (1998), he created the storyline in which Laurie Strode has faked her own death and taken on a new identity as a specific way of [[retroactive continuity|retconning]] the character's death in ''Halloween 4''. In Williamson's original treatment, there are scenes in which a Hillcrest student does a report on Michael Myers' killing spree, mentioning the death of Jamie, complete with flashbacks to 4-6 mentioned in the text. \"Keri\"/Laurie responds to hearing the student's report on the death of her daughter by going into a restroom and throwing up.<ref>[[Kevin Williamson (screenwriter)|Williamson, Kevin]]. \"[http://soma.sbcc.edu/users/DaVega/FILMPRO_175/Filmpro_175_Film_Writing/TREATMENTS/treatmentexaple_4_halloween7.pdf Halloween 7 treatment] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720041914/http://soma.sbcc.edu/users/DaVega/FILMPRO_175/Filmpro_175_Film_Writing/TREATMENTS/treatmentexaple_4_halloween7.pdf |date=2011-07-20 }}\"</ref> In a controversial decision, director [[Steve Miner]] retconned the series with ''Halloween H20: 20 Years Later''. This installment retained Laurie's faked death from Williamson's treatment, revealing that she did so in order to avoid detection by her relentless brother. Under a new identity, Laurie has fled to Summer Glen, [[California]], along with her only son, John Tate ([[Josh Hartnett]]). However, to focus more on the Laurie Strode character, the events of parts 4, 5, and 6 are implicitly written out of the continuity, thus erasing the Jamie Lloyd character from the canon.\n\nEarly on, the script for ''[[Halloween (2018 film)|Halloween]]'' (2018) had Jamie appear alongside Laurie for the first time. However, subsequent rewrites changed her to 'Karen',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/movie/3534092/halloween-ending/|title=Early Draft of 'Halloween' Script Changed Laurie Strode's fate|last=Miska|first=Brad|date=November 19, 2018|website=Bloody Disgusting|access-date=November 26, 2018}}</ref> followed by the casting of an actress with no resemblance to Danielle Harris.<ref>{{cite web|last1=N'Duka|first1=Amanda|title=Judy Greer In Talks To Join Jamie Lee Curtis In \u2018Halloween\u2019 Reboot|url=http://deadline.com/2017/10/judy-greer-jamie-lee-curtis-halloween-reboot-1202180641/|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|accessdate=2 October 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171003114837/http://deadline.com/2017/10/judy-greer-jamie-lee-curtis-halloween-reboot-1202180641/|archivedate=3 October 2017}}</ref> Even before those early plans were publicly known, Harris objected, feeling strongly about Laurie having a daughter that was not Jamie, but her appeals to the production company were dismissed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/movie/3468708/danielle-harris-talks-next-years-halloween-im-bummed-heres/|title=Danielle Harris Talks Next Year's \"Halloween\"; \"I'm Bummed Out...And Here's Why\"|last=Squires|first=John|date=November 7, 2017|website=Bloody Disgusting|access-date=November 26, 2018}}</ref> The film also, which is a direct sequel to the original film, disregards Michael as the brother of Laurie Strode.\n\n===Literature===\nJamie Lloyd's first literary appearance was in October 1988, in Nicholas Grabowsky's novelization of ''Halloween 4''.<ref>{{cite book |first=Nicholas |last=Grabowsky |title=Halloween IV |date=October 1988 |publisher=Critics Choice Paperbacks/Lorevan Publishing |isbn=1555472923}}</ref>\n\nThe official ''Halloween: 30 Years of Terror'' comic book, taking place in the new continuity, has an adult Tommy Doyle illustrating comic books. Various elements from the fourth through sixth movies can be seen on his books, one of which is Jamie.\n\nThe comic ''Halloween: The Mark of Thorn'' features Jamie, as well as Tommy Doyle, Rachel Carruthers and the Man in Black.\n\n==Casting==\n[[Melissa Joan Hart]] had auditioned for the role, among various other girls.<ref name=\"BD\">{{Cite web |url=http://bloody-disgusting.com/editorials/3461076/10-fun-facts-may-not-know-halloween-4/ |title=10 Fun Facts You May Not Know About 'Halloween 4: The Return of Michael Myers' |last=Pauley |first=Patti |date=October 21, 2017 |website=[[Bloody Disgusting]] |access-date=October 22, 2017}}</ref> Up against her was Danielle Harris, who had previously starred in ''[[One Life to Live]]'' as Samantha Garretson; Harris was ultimately cast in the role after auditioning in New York.{{sfn|Little|2013|loc=event occurs at 7:25}} Jamie Lloyd was Danielle Harris' first feature film role, for which she appears at horror conventions and on ''Halloween'' series-related websites. Harris sought to reprise the role for the sixth installment, now titled ''Halloween: The Curse of Michael Myers'', but the producers and [[Dimension Films]] reportedly refused to pay her the $5,000 she requested, and she was not fond of the script. The role was instead given to actress [[J. C. Brandy]], who was a ''Halloween'' fan herself.<ref>[http://www.iconsoffright.com/IV_Dan.htm Dan Farrands interview]</ref> Harris made her eventual return to the series as [[Annie Brackett]] in [[Rob Zombie]]'s ''[[Halloween (2007 film)|Halloween]]'' remake, as well as its [[Halloween II (2009 film)|subsequent sequel]].\n\n==Other notes==\nIn the films, the uncertainty of Jamie's age stems from a discrepancy between ''Halloween 4'' and ''5''. In the former film, set in late October 1988, Jamie's foster sister, [[List of Halloween (franchise) characters#Rachel Carruthers|Rachel Carruthers]] ([[Ellie Cornell]]) wonders why Jamie continues staying up so late. She asks, \"You are going for a record here? The Seven-Year-Old Insomniacs' Hall of Fame?\", suggesting that she is born in 1981. The latter film is set one year later in late October 1989. Rachel and Jamie's adolescent friend [[List of Halloween (franchise) characters#Tina Williams|Tina Williams]] ([[Wendy Kaplan]]) exclaims to [[Samuel Loomis|Dr. Sam Loomis]] ([[Donald Pleasence]]) that \"Jamie\u2019s a nine-year-old girl!\"\n\nIn the novelization of the fourth film, ''Halloween IV'' (1988; revised edition, 2003) by Nicholas Grabowsky, Jamie is six years old, which implicitly dates her birth to 1982. According to ''H4'', Laurie legally died 11 months earlier in November 1987 and Richard and Darlene Carruthers are Jamie's foster parents. In ''H5'', it is apparent that Jamie had been adopted assuming the name \"Jamie Carruthers\".\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Halloween series}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lloyd, Jamie}}\n[[Category:Female horror film characters]]\n[[Category:Halloween (franchise) characters]]\n[[Category:Fictional adoptees]]\n[[Category:Fictional telepaths]]\n[[Category:Fictional mute characters]]\n[[Category:Fictional characters from Illinois]]\n[[Category:Child characters in film]]\n[[Category:Film characters introduced in 1988]]\n[[Category:Teenage characters in film]]\n[[Category:Fictional victims of child abuse]]\n[[Category:Fictional teenage parents]]\n[[Category:Fictional sole survivors]]\n[[Category:Final girls]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|the British theater director|Jamie Lloyd (director)}}\n{{In-universe|subject = film|category = film|date = December 2010}}\n\n{{Infobox character\n|series        = [[Halloween (franchise)|Halloween]]\n|image         = Jamie Lloyd.jpg\n|image_size    = 250px\n|caption       = [[Danielle Harris]] as Jamie Lloyd in the fourth film\n|creator       = [[Alan B. McElroy]]\n|portrayer     = [[Danielle Harris]] (''Halloween [[Halloween 4: The Return of Michael Myers|4]]'' & ''[[Halloween 5: The Revenge of Michael Myers|5]]'') <br>[[J. C. Brandy]] (''Halloween [[Halloween: The Curse of Michael Myers|6]]'')\n|first          = ''[[Halloween 4: The Return of Michael Myers]]''\n|last           = ''[[Halloween: The Curse of Michael Myers]]''\n|family        = [[Laurie Strode]] (deceased mother) \n|children      = Stephen Lloyd (son/cousin in Producer's Cut; orphaned)\n|relatives     = [[List of Halloween (franchise) characters#Judith Myers|Judith Myers]] (deceased maternal aunt) <br>[[Michael Myers (Halloween)|Michael Myers]] (maternal uncle) <br> Morgan Strode (deceased maternal grandfather) <br> Pamela Strode (deceased maternal grandmother) <br> Richard Carruthers (foster father) <br> Darlene Carruthers (foster mother) <br> Rachel Carruthers (deceased foster sister) <br> John Strode (deceased maternal great-uncle) <br> Debra Strode (deceased maternal great-aunt) <br> Tim Strode (deceased maternal first cousin once removed) <br> Kara Strode (maternal first cousin once removed) <br> Danny Strode (maternal second cousin)\n}}\n'''Jamie Lloyd''' is a [[character (arts)|fictional character]] in the [[Halloween (franchise)|''Halloween'' franchise]] and the main [[protagonist]] of ''[[Halloween 4: The Return of Michael Myers|Halloween 4]]'' and ''[[Halloween 5: The Revenge of Michael Myers|5]]'' and also appears  in a less prominent role in ''[[Halloween: The Curse of Michael Myers]]''. The character was created by [[Alan B. McElroy]] and portrayed by actress [[Danielle Harris]] in the fourth and fifth films of the series, while [[J.C. Brandy]] portrays her in the sixth.\n\nThe character was created after [[Jamie Lee Curtis]] declined to return as [[Laurie Strode]] for the fourth film due to not wanting to continue her participation in the film. As a result, her character was written out and died in a car accident, which is briefly explained in the film. Originally, the character was named Brittany \"Britti\" Lloyd. Britti's name was later changed to Jamie, a homage to Laurie Strode actress [[Jamie Lee Curtis]]. The fourth film introduced Laurie's daughter, Jamie Lloyd. As the daughter of Laurie, she is also the niece of infamous [[serial killer]] [[Michael Myers (Halloween)|Michael Myers]] and his first victim, [[List of Halloween (franchise) characters#Judith Myers|Judith Myers]].\n\n==Appearances==\n===Films===\nFirst appearing in ''[[Halloween 4: The Return of Michael Myers]]'' (1988), Jamie is [[Laurie Strode]]'s daughter, as well as the niece of [[#Judith Myers|Judith]] and [[Michael Myers (Halloween)|Michael Myers]], which she and all of Haddonfield know about. Her father is unknown since her surname was never explained or elaborated in films where it came from when she appeared. She is put in the care of a foster family, the Carruthers, and later [[adoption|adopted]] after Laurie dies in a car crash. She suffers from nightmares about Michael and is bullied at school for being related to \"The Boogeyman\". On October 30, 1988, Michael is being transferred out of Ridgemont Federal Sanitarium back to Smith's Grove. While in the transfer ambulance, he recovers from his ten-year coma upon learning the existence of his niece. Accordingly, he kills the two medical attendants and the two drivers. While making his way back to his hometown, he also kills a mechanic and a waitress. In Haddonfield, while on the trail for Jamie, Michael kills the Carruthers' Golden Retriever Sundae, a worker at the power plant which causes a blackout of the entire town, the entire police force, the deputy, the police chief's daughter Kelly, Rachel's boyfriend Brady, and 4 men from a vigilante mob. Escaping from town, Jamie cowers in a pick-up truck as Rachel hits Michael head on, throwing him off the road and knocking him out. Despite Rachel's orders, Jamie goes over to him and holds his hand. The police tell Jamie to drop to the ground and shoot Michael many times, causing him to fall into an abandoned mine shaft, which then collapses on top of him. Later, back in her foster home, Jamie is possessed by Michael's spirit and attacks her foster mother. When screams are heard from upstairs, Dr. Loomis walks over to the staircase seeing Jamie poised at the top holding a pair of bloody scissors, similar to Michael when he killed his older sister Judith. Sheriff Ben Meeker (Beau Starr) restrains Loomis from shooting her, and both men, Mr. Carruthers, and Rachel watch in horror, realizing that Jamie is following in Michael's footsteps. ''[[Halloween 5: The Revenge of Michael Myers]]'' (1989), taking place a year later, has a severely traumatized Jamie housed in the Haddonfield Children's Clinic. She has now been rendered mute and suffers from nightmares and seizures, and being treated for attacking her foster mother under Michael's influence, though her foster mother survived. Early in the film, a brick, bearing a note reading, \"The evil child must die,\" is thrown through her window.  When Michael ([[Donald L. Shanks]]) awakens from a year-long coma, she exhibits signs of a [[Telepathy|telepathic]] link with her uncle, eventually regains the ability to speak, and has seizures whenever her uncle kills someone. Michael kills Rachel, four of Rachel's friends, two cops, and the Carruthers' new dog, a Doberman Pinscher named Max, while in pursuit of Jamie. Towards the end, Loomis takes Jamie to the old Myers house and successfully lures Michael into the house by having Jamie reenact her aunt Judith's final moments. Despite the doctor's pleas with Michael to fight his rage and seek redemption through a positive relationship with Jamie, Myers tracks down his niece in Judith Myers' deserted bedroom. Michael finds Jamie, but before he can kill her, she tries to appeal to her uncle's humanity. At Jamie's request, Michael takes off his mask. However, Jamie touches Michael's face, sending him into a fit of rage. Using Jamie as bait, Loomis catches Michael in a net, shoots him with tranquilizer darts, and beats him unconscious with a wooden beam. Michael is manacled and locked up in the local jail, awaiting transport to a maximum-security facility, where, Meeker says, he will remain \"until the day he dies,\" to which Jamie responds, \"He'll never die.\" After Jamie is escorted out to be taken home, a mysterious \"Man in Black\" arrives and attacks the police station. Jamie goes back inside to find that eight police officers have been gunned down, including Meeker, and that her uncle has escaped, prompting her to begin sobbing in terror. In ''[[Halloween: The Curse of Michael Myers]]'' (1995), the Man in Black kidnaps Jamie immediately after the shoot-out and has kept her and Michael ([[George P. Wilbur]]) in captivity for the past six years. 15-year-old Jamie gives birth to a boy on the night of October 30, 1995. [[Samuel Loomis|Dr. Loomis]] and Tommy Doyle ([[Paul Rudd]]), whom Laurie Strode was babysitting on Halloween 1978, attempt to rescue Jamie after hearing her plea for help on a local radio station. Michael kills Jamie by impaling her on a corn [[threshing machine|thresher]] and turning it on, disemboweling her. Before being killed, Jamie hides her [[infant]], who is found by Tommy. The Man in Black is revealed to be Loomis' former medical colleague [[List of Halloween (franchise) characters#Dr. Terence Wynn|Dr. Terence Wynn]] ([[Mitchell Ryan]]). He and most of his staff are revealed to be a [[Druid]] cult headquartered in the subterranean levels of the Smith's Grove Sanitarium, the place where Michael was committed after killing his sister Judith. They are responsible for Michael's actions, placing an ancient curse on him to kill his family to ward off sickness and death. By the end of the movie, it is implied that Dr. Wynn has been trying and failing to breed the ultimate evil using Michael's DNA and female patients of the sanitarium in [[in vitro fertilisation|in-vitro fertilization]] experiments; finally reaching a success with Jamie's baby after she had been tested on. In the original cut of the film, Jamie does not die at the beginning of the film, and instead survives a knife attack by Michael in the barn. She remains in a [[coma]] and is taken to the hospital, where Loomis and Wynn visit her. Later, an unseen person, later revealed to be Wynn, shoots the unconscious Jamie in the head with a silenced pistol.\n\nWhen screenwriter [[Kevin Williamson (screenwriter)|Kevin Williamson]] first outlined ''[[Halloween H20: 20 Years Later]]'' (1998), he created the storyline in which Laurie Strode has faked her own death and taken on a new identity as a specific way of [[retroactive continuity|retconning]] the character's death in ''Halloween 4''. In Williamson's original treatment, there are scenes in which a Hillcrest student does a report on Michael Myers' killing spree, mentioning the death of Jamie, complete with flashbacks to 4-6 mentioned in the text. \"Keri\"/Laurie responds to hearing the student's report on the death of her daughter by going into a restroom and throwing up.<ref>[[Kevin Williamson (screenwriter)|Williamson, Kevin]]. \"[http://soma.sbcc.edu/users/DaVega/FILMPRO_175/Filmpro_175_Film_Writing/TREATMENTS/treatmentexaple_4_halloween7.pdf Halloween 7 treatment] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720041914/http://soma.sbcc.edu/users/DaVega/FILMPRO_175/Filmpro_175_Film_Writing/TREATMENTS/treatmentexaple_4_halloween7.pdf |date=2011-07-20 }}\"</ref> In a controversial decision, director [[Steve Miner]] retconned the series with ''Halloween H20: 20 Years Later''. This installment retained Laurie's faked death from Williamson's treatment, revealing that she did so in order to avoid detection by her relentless brother. Under a new identity, Laurie has fled to Summer Glen, [[California]], along with her only son, John Tate ([[Josh Hartnett]]). However, to focus more on the Laurie Strode character, the events of parts 4, 5, and 6 are implicitly written out of the continuity, thus erasing the Jamie Lloyd character from the canon.\n\nEarly on, the script for ''[[Halloween (2018 film)|Halloween]]'' (2018) had Jamie appear alongside Laurie for the first time. However, subsequent rewrites changed her to 'Karen',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/movie/3534092/halloween-ending/|title=Early Draft of 'Halloween' Script Changed Laurie Strode's fate|last=Miska|first=Brad|date=November 19, 2018|website=Bloody Disgusting|access-date=November 26, 2018}}</ref> followed by the casting of an actress with no resemblance to Danielle Harris.<ref>{{cite web|last1=N'Duka|first1=Amanda|title=Judy Greer In Talks To Join Jamie Lee Curtis In \u2018Halloween\u2019 Reboot|url=http://deadline.com/2017/10/judy-greer-jamie-lee-curtis-halloween-reboot-1202180641/|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|accessdate=2 October 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171003114837/http://deadline.com/2017/10/judy-greer-jamie-lee-curtis-halloween-reboot-1202180641/|archivedate=3 October 2017}}</ref> Even before those early plans were publicly known, Harris objected, feeling strongly about Laurie having a daughter that was not Jamie, but her appeals to the production company were dismissed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/movie/3468708/danielle-harris-talks-next-years-halloween-im-bummed-heres/|title=Danielle Harris Talks Next Year's \"Halloween\"; \"I'm Bummed Out...And Here's Why\"|last=Squires|first=John|date=November 7, 2017|website=Bloody Disgusting|access-date=November 26, 2018}}</ref> The film also, which is a direct sequel to the original film, disregards Michael as the brother of Laurie Strode.\n\n===Literature===\nJamie Lloyd's first literary appearance was in October 1988, in Nicholas Grabowsky's novelization of ''Halloween 4''.<ref>{{cite book |first=Nicholas |last=Grabowsky |title=Halloween IV |date=October 1988 |publisher=Critics Choice Paperbacks/Lorevan Publishing |isbn=1555472923}}</ref>\n\nThe official ''Halloween: 30 Years of Terror'' comic book, taking place in the new continuity, has an adult Tommy Doyle illustrating comic books. Various elements from the fourth through sixth movies can be seen on his books, one of which is Jamie.\n\nThe comic ''Halloween: The Mark of Thorn'' features Jamie, as well as Tommy Doyle, Rachel Carruthers and the Man in Black.\n\n==Casting==\n[[Melissa Joan Hart]] had auditioned for the role, among various other girls.<ref name=\"BD\">{{Cite web |url=http://bloody-disgusting.com/editorials/3461076/10-fun-facts-may-not-know-halloween-4/ |title=10 Fun Facts You May Not Know About 'Halloween 4: The Return of Michael Myers' |last=Pauley |first=Patti |date=October 21, 2017 |website=[[Bloody Disgusting]] |access-date=October 22, 2017}}</ref> Up against her was Danielle Harris, who had previously starred in ''[[One Life to Live]]'' as Samantha Garretson; Harris was ultimately cast in the role after auditioning in New York.{{sfn|Little|2013|loc=event occurs at 7:25}} Jamie Lloyd was Danielle Harris' first feature film role, for which she appears at horror conventions and on ''Halloween'' series-related websites. Harris sought to reprise the role for the sixth installment, now titled ''Halloween: The Curse of Michael Myers'', but the producers and [[Dimension Films]] reportedly refused to pay her the $5,000 she requested, and she was not fond of the script. The role was instead given to actress [[J. C. Brandy]], who was a ''Halloween'' fan herself.<ref>[http://www.iconsoffright.com/IV_Dan.htm Dan Farrands interview]</ref> Harris made her eventual return to the series as [[Annie Brackett]] in [[Rob Zombie]]'s ''[[Halloween (2007 film)|Halloween]]'' remake, as well as its [[Halloween II (2009 film)|subsequent sequel]].\n\n==Other notes==\nIn the films, the uncertainty of Jamie\u2019s age stems from a discrepancy between ''Halloween 4'' and ''5''. In the former film, set in late October 1988, Jamie's foster sister, [[List of Halloween (franchise) characters#Rachel Carruthers|Rachel Carruthers]] ([[Ellie Cornell]]) wonders why Jamie continues staying up so late. She asks, \"You are going for a record here? The Seven-Year-Old Insomniacs' Hall of Fame?\", suggesting that she is born in 1981. The latter film is set one year later in late October 1989. Rachel and Jamie\u2019s adolescent friend [[List of Halloween (franchise) characters#Tina Williams|Tina Williams]] ([[Wendy Kaplan]]) exclaims to [[Samuel Loomis|Dr. Sam Loomis]] ([[Donald Pleasence]]) that \"Jamie\u2019s a nine-year-old girl!\"\n\nIn the novelization of the fourth film, ''Halloween IV'' (1988; revised edition, 2003) by Nicholas Grabowsky, Jamie is six years old, which implicitly dates her birth to 1982. According to ''H4'', Laurie legally died 11 months earlier in November 1987 and Richard and Darlene Carruthers are Jamie\u2019s foster parents. In ''H5'', it is apparent that Jamie had been adopted assuming the name \"Jamie Carruthers\".\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Halloween series}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lloyd, Jamie}}\n[[Category:Female horror film characters]]\n[[Category:Halloween (franchise) characters]]\n[[Category:Fictional adoptees]]\n[[Category:Fictional telepaths]]\n[[Category:Fictional mute characters]]\n[[Category:Fictional characters from Illinois]]\n[[Category:Child characters in film]]\n[[Category:Film characters introduced in 1988]]\n[[Category:Teenage characters in film]]\n[[Category:Fictional victims of child abuse]]\n[[Category:Fictional teenage parents]]\n[[Category:Fictional sole survivors]]\n[[Category:Final girls]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eOther notes:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's (3)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jamie_Lloyd"}
{"title_page": "Isolation (Joy Division song)", "text_new": "{{Infobox song\n| name     = Isolation\n| cover    =\n| alt      =\n| type     =\n| artist   = [[Joy Division]]\n| album    = [[Closer (Joy Division album)|Closer]]\n| released = 1980\n| format   =\n| recorded = 18\u201330 March 1980 at [[Britannia Row Studios]], [[London]], [[United Kingdom]]\n| studio   =\n| venue    =\n| genre    = [[Gothic rock]]<ref name=\"goth\">{{cite journal |author=McCullough, Dave |title=Closer to the edge (Joy Division Closer album review) |work=Sounds |date=26 July 1980 |quote=Young men in dark silhouettes, some darker than others, looking inwards, looking out, discovering the same horror and describing it with the same dark strokes of gothic rock.}}</ref>\n| length   = 2:52\n| label    = [[Factory Records|Factory]]\n| writer   = {{hlist|[[Bernard Sumner]]|[[Peter Hook]]|[[Stephen Morris (musician)|Stephen Morris]]|[[Ian Curtis]] <ref>[http://www.ascap.com/ace/search.cfm?requesttimeout=300&mode=results&searchstr=480210180&search_in=i&search_type=exact&search_det=t,s,w,p,b,v&results_pp=30&start=1 Ascap entry]</ref>}}\n| producer = {{hlist|[[Martin Hannett]]|Joy Division}}\n| misc       = \n{{Audio sample\n | type = song\n | file = Isolation.ogg\n}}\n}}\n\n\"'''Isolation'''\" is a 1980 song appearing on the [[post-punk]] band [[Joy Division]]'s second and final album ''[[Closer (Joy Division album)|Closer]]''.  The song is based upon an electronic drum beat by [[Stephen Paul David Morris|Stephen Morris]], accompanied by a high-pitched keyboard line by [[Bernard Sumner]]. Midway through the song, a rushing drum and [[Hi-hat (instrument)|hi-hat]] motif come in, propelling the song toward its dramatic end. \n\n==Composition==\n\"Isolation\" is an [[gothic rock]] song which contains elements of [[synth pop]] and [[electronic music]] that lasts for a duration of two minutes and fifty-two seconds.<ref name=\"Joy Division\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.musicnotes.com/sheetmusic/mtd.asp?ppn=MN0118801|title=Joy Division 'Isolation' Sheet Music in C Major - Download & Print|author=Joy Division|work=Musicnotes.com|publisher=[[Universal Music Publishing Group]]|access-date=March 26, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Raggett\"/> According to the [[sheet music]] published at Musicnotes.com by [[Universal Music Publishing Group]], it is written in the [[time signature]] of [[Time signature#Most frequent time signatures|common time]], with a  [[tempo]] of 148 [[Tempo#Beats per minute|beats per minute]].<ref name=\"Joy Division\"/> \"Isolation\" is played in the [[Key (music)|key]] of [[C major]], while Ian Curtis's [[vocal range]] spans one [[Octave|octave]], from the low-note of [[B (musical note)|B<sub>3</sub>]] to the high-note of [[B (musical note)|B<sub>4</sub>]].<ref name=\"Joy Division\"/> The song has a basic sequence of G\u2013F\u2013G in the verses, changes to B\u2013A\u2013G\u2013F\u2013G at the chorus and follows G\u2013F\u2013G\u2013G\u2013G during the [[Outro (music)|outro]] as its [[chord progression]].<ref name=\"Joy Division\"/>\u00a0\n\nThe song harbors atypical [[song structure]] and vocal delivery. Its musical arrangement employs a [[False_ending#Music|false ending]] where the band abruptly ceases, only for the recording to suddenly return with noisy [[Feedback (music)|feedback]] of a snippet before coming to a blunt end.<ref name=\"Raggett\"/> \"Isolation\" is built on harsh [[electronic drum]]s and a rolling, stabbing bassline. In place of a guitar melody, a cascading high-pitched [[synth]] [[Melody|line]] runs throughout the entire composition as its driving instrument.<ref name=\"Raggett\"/> Ian Curtis's sings poetic lyrics that illustrate an abstract portrait of the titular subject. His chilling lines express a sense of a connection and yearning after the impossible: \"But if you could just see the beauty, these things I could never describe.\"<ref name=\"Raggett\">{{cite web|title=Isolation \u2013 Joy Division|url=https://www.allmusic.com/song/isolation-mt0027067082|website=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=2020-03-26|author=Raggett, Ned|authorlink=}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\n[[AllMusic]]'s Ned Raggett complimented \"Isolation,\" writing, \"the song structure and delivery is all Joy Division and as such makes the song an intriguing twist on a style and a highlight of the excellent ''[[Closer (Joy Division album)|Closer]]'' album.\"<ref name=\"Raggett\"/>\n\n==Production==\nJoy Division Bassist [[Peter Hook]] said the ending came as the [[serendipity|serendipitous]] result of Martin Hannett's efforts to rescue the original master tape from a botched edit by a junior sound engineer.\n\n==Personnel==\n\n* [[Ian Curtis]] - Lead vocals\n* [[Bernard Sumner]] - Guitar, synthesizer\n* [[Peter Hook]] - Bass guitar\n* [[Stephen Paul David Morris|Stephen Morris]] - Electronic drums\n\n==Covers==\nThe song has been covered many times including by:\n*[[New Order (band)|New Order]] played an electronic-based cover in a [[John Peel|Peel Session]] in 1998, released in the [[In Session (New Order album)|In Session]] compilation (2004).\n*Northern Irish [[alternative metal]] band [[Therapy?]] covered the song on their 1994 album ''[[Troublegum]]''. This version also incorporates elements from [[Atrocity Exhibition (Joy Division song)|Atrocity Exhibition]].\n*In 1995, a cover by [[The Smashing Pumpkins]] spin-off band [[Starchildren]] appeared on the tribute album ''[[A Means to an End: The Music of Joy Division]]''.\n*Industrial band [[WTII Records|Dessau]] released the [[Al Jourgensen]] produced 12\" single in late 1988.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Discogs master|133849|Isolation|type=single}}\n* {{MetroLyrics song|joy-division|isolation}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n* Usage in film and television: see [https://web.archive.org/web/20170216192009/http://www.imdb.com/name/nm1920312/ \"Joy Division - Soundtrack. 'Isolation'\"] at the [[Internet Movie Database]]\n\n{{Joy Division}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Isolation (Joy Division Song)}}\n[[Category:1980 songs]]\n[[Category:Joy Division songs]]\n[[Category:Songs about loneliness]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Bernard Sumner]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Peter Hook]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Stephen Morris (musician)]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Ian Curtis]]\n\n\n{{1980s-song-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox song\n| name     = Isolation\n| cover    =\n| alt      =\n| type     =\n| artist   = [[Joy Division]]\n| album    = [[Closer (Joy Division album)|Closer]]\n| released = 1980\n| format   =\n| recorded = 18\u201330 March 1980 at [[Britannia Row Studios]], [[London]], [[United Kingdom]]\n| studio   =\n| venue    =\n| genre    = [[Gothic rock]]<ref name=\"goth\">{{cite journal |author=McCullough, Dave |title=Closer to the edge (Joy Division Closer album review) |work=Sounds |date=26 July 1980 |quote=Young men in dark silhouettes, some darker than others, looking inwards, looking out, discovering the same horror and describing it with the same dark strokes of gothic rock.}}</ref>\n| length   = 2:52\n| label    = [[Factory Records|Factory]]\n| writer   = {{hlist|[[Bernard Sumner]]|[[Peter Hook]]|[[Stephen Morris (musician)|Stephen Morris]]|[[Ian Curtis]] <ref>[http://www.ascap.com/ace/search.cfm?requesttimeout=300&mode=results&searchstr=480210180&search_in=i&search_type=exact&search_det=t,s,w,p,b,v&results_pp=30&start=1 Ascap entry]</ref>}}\n| producer = {{hlist|[[Martin Hannett]]|Joy Division}}\n| misc       = \n{{Audio sample\n | type = song\n | file = Isolation.ogg\n}}\n}}\n\n\"'''Isolation'''\" is a 1980 song appearing on the [[post-punk]] band [[Joy Division]]'s second and final album ''[[Closer (Joy Division album)|Closer]]''.  The song is based upon an electronic drum beat by [[Stephen Paul David Morris|Stephen Morris]], accompanied by a high-pitched keyboard line by [[Bernard Sumner]]. Midway through the song, a rushing drum and [[Hi-hat (instrument)|hi-hat]] motif come in, propelling the song toward its dramatic end. \n\n==Composition==\n\"Isolation\" is an [[gothic rock]] song which contains elements of [[synth pop]] and [[electronic music]] that lasts for a duration of two minutes and fifty-two seconds.<ref name=\"Joy Division\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.musicnotes.com/sheetmusic/mtd.asp?ppn=MN0118801|title=Joy Division 'Isolation' Sheet Music in C Major - Download & Print|author=Joy Division|work=Musicnotes.com|publisher=[[Universal Music Publishing Group]]|access-date=March 26, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Raggett\"/> According to the [[sheet music]] published at Musicnotes.com by [[Universal Music Publishing Group]], it is written in the [[time signature]] of [[Time signature#Most frequent time signatures|common time]], with a  [[tempo]] of 148 [[Tempo#Beats per minute|beats per minute]].<ref name=\"Joy Division\"/> \"Isolation\" is composed in the [[Key (music)|key]] of [[C major]], while Ian Curtis's [[vocal range]] spans one [[Octave|octave]], from the low-note of [[B (musical note)|B<sub>3</sub>]] to the high-note of [[B (musical note)|B<sub>4</sub>]].<ref name=\"Joy Division\"/> The song has a basic sequence of G\u2013F\u2013G in the verses, changes to B\u2013A\u2013G\u2013F\u2013G at the chorus and follows G\u2013F\u2013G\u2013G\u2013G during the [[Outro (music)|outro]] as its [[chord progression]].<ref name=\"Joy Division\"/>\u00a0\n\nThe song harbors atypical [[song structure]] and vocal delivery. Its musical arrangement employs a [[False_ending#Music|false ending]] where the band abruptly ceases, only for the recording to suddenly return with noisy [[Feedback (music)|feedback]] of a snippet before coming to a blunt end.<ref name=\"Raggett\"/> \"Isolation\" is built on harsh [[electronic drum]]s and a rolling, stabbing bassline. In place of a guitar melody, a cascading high-pitched [[synth]] [[Melody|line]] runs throughout the entire composition as its driving instrument.<ref name=\"Raggett\"/> Ian Curtis's sings poetic lyrics that illustrate an abstract portrait of the titular subject. His chilling lines express a sense of a connection and yearning after the impossible: \"But if you could just see the beauty, these things I could never describe.\"<ref name=\"Raggett\">{{cite web|title=Isolation \u2013 Joy Division|url=https://www.allmusic.com/song/isolation-mt0027067082|website=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=2020-03-26|author=Raggett, Ned|authorlink=}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\n[[AllMusic]]'s Ned Raggett complimented \"Isolation,\" writing, \"the song structure and delivery is all Joy Division and as such makes the song an intriguing twist on a style and a highlight of the excellent ''[[Closer (Joy Division album)|Closer]]'' album.\"<ref name=\"Raggett\"/>\n\n==Production==\nJoy Division Bassist [[Peter Hook]] said the ending came as the [[serendipity|serendipitous]] result of Martin Hannett's efforts to rescue the original master tape from a botched edit by a junior sound engineer.\n\n==Personnel==\n\n* [[Ian Curtis]] - Lead vocals\n* [[Bernard Sumner]] - Guitar, synthesizer\n* [[Peter Hook]] - Bass guitar\n* [[Stephen Paul David Morris|Stephen Morris]] - Electronic drums\n\n==Covers==\nThe song has been covered many times including by:\n*[[New Order (band)|New Order]] played an electronic-based cover in a [[John Peel|Peel Session]] in 1998, released in the [[In Session (New Order album)|In Session]] compilation (2004).\n*Northern Irish [[alternative metal]] band [[Therapy?]] covered the song on their 1994 album ''[[Troublegum]]''. This version also incorporates elements from [[Atrocity Exhibition (Joy Division song)|Atrocity Exhibition]].\n*In 1995, a cover by [[The Smashing Pumpkins]] spin-off band [[Starchildren]] appeared on the tribute album ''[[A Means to an End: The Music of Joy Division]]''.\n*Industrial band [[WTII Records|Dessau]] released the [[Al Jourgensen]] produced 12\" single in late 1988.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Discogs master|133849|Isolation|type=single}}\n* {{MetroLyrics song|joy-division|isolation}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n* Usage in film and television: see [https://web.archive.org/web/20170216192009/http://www.imdb.com/name/nm1920312/ \"Joy Division - Soundtrack. 'Isolation'\"] at the [[Internet Movie Database]]\n\n{{Joy Division}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Isolation (Joy Division Song)}}\n[[Category:1980 songs]]\n[[Category:Joy Division songs]]\n[[Category:Songs about loneliness]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Bernard Sumner]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Peter Hook]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Stephen Morris (musician)]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Ian Curtis]]\n\n\n{{1980s-song-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ceoil", "label": "safe", "comment": "ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Isolation_(Joy_Division_song)"}
{"title_page": "Stargirl (TV series)", "text_new": "{{short description|Upcoming American drama web television series}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = Stargirl\n| image                    = Stargirl TV series.jpeg\n| caption                  = \n| genre                    = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Drama (film and television)|Drama]]\n* [[Superhero fiction|Superhero]]\n}}\n| creator                  = [[Geoff Johns]]\n| based_on                 = {{based on|[[Courtney Whitmore|Stargirl]]|Geoff Johns|Lee Moder}}\n| starring                 = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Brec Bassinger]]\n* Anjelika Washington\n* [[Yvette Monreal]]\n* {{nowrap|Christopher James Baker}}\n* [[Joy Osmanski]]\n* [[Neil Hopkins]]\n* [[Nelson Lee]]\n* [[Luke Wilson]]\n* Cameron Gellman\n* [[Amy Smart]]\n* [[Neil Jackson]]\n* Hunter Sansone\n* Trae Romano\n}}\n| composer                 = [[Pinar Toprak]]\n| country                  = United States\n| language                 = English\n| num_seasons              = \n| num_episodes             = \n| list_episodes            = \n| executive_producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* Geoff Johns\n* [[Greg Berlanti]]\n* [[Sarah Schechter]]\n}}\n| producer                 = \n| cinematography           = \n| editor                   = \n| camera                   = \n| runtime                  = \n| company                  = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Mad Ghost Productions]]\n* [[Berlanti Productions]]\n* [[DC Entertainment]]\n* [[Warner Bros. Television]]\n}}\n| network                  = [[DC Universe (streaming service)|DC Universe]]\n| picture_format           = [[1080i]] ([[High-definition television|HDTV]])\n| audio_format             = \n| first_aired              = <!--{{Start date|2020|5|18}}-->\n| last_aired               = \n| website                  = \n}}\n\n'''''Stargirl''''' is an upcoming American [[Drama (film and television)|drama]] [[web television]] series created by [[Geoff Johns]] that will air on [[DC Universe (streaming service)|DC Universe]]. It is based on the [[DC Comics]] [[superhero]] [[Courtney Whitmore|of the same name]] created by Johns and Lee Moder. The series follows Courtney Whitmore, portrayed by [[Brec Bassinger]], who discovers the cosmic staff and becomes the inspiration for a new generation of superheroes who become the [[Justice Society of America]].\n\nDC Universe ordered the series in July 2018. Bassinger was cast in September 2018, with additional castings for her family members, the Justice Society of America, and the [[Injustice Society]] through February 2019. Filming for the series began by March 2019 in the [[Atlanta metropolitan area]] in Georgia.\n\n''Stargirl'' is set to premiere on May 18, 2020. The series will also air the following day on [[The CW]], as well as be available on The CW's digital platforms. Ahead of the series premiere, characters from the series were featured in the [[Arrowverse]] crossover \"[[Crisis on Infinite Earths (Arrowverse)|Crisis on Infinite Earths]]\", establishing ''Stargirl'' as existing on [[Earth-2 (Arrowverse post-Crisis)|a parallel earth to the Arrowverse series]].\n\n==Premise==\nHigh school sophomore [[Courtney Whitmore]] discovers a powerful cosmic staff, and after learning that her step-father [[Pat Dugan]] used to be a hero sidekick, becomes the inspiration for a new generation of superheroes.<ref name=\"Bassinger\" />\n\n==Cast and characters==\n===Main===\n* [[Brec Bassinger]] as [[Courtney Whitmore|Courtney Whitmore / Stargirl]]:<br />A high school sophomore who discovers a powerful cosmic staff and becomes the hero Stargirl.<ref name=\"Bassinger\" /> She is the leader of the new [[Justice Society of America]].<ref name=\"IGNJSAReveal\" /> Bassinger did not look at the previous portrayals of the character by [[Britt Irvin]] on ''[[Smallville]]'' or [[Sarah Grey]] on ''[[Legends of Tomorrow]]'' because they were depicted as \"older, more mature version[s]\" of Stargirl. Bassinger added the series followed the comic ''[[Stars and S.T.R.I.P.E.]]'' more \"in that she's young, high school, naive, which I wanted to bring that into this version of Stargirl.\"<ref name=\"IGNJSAReveal\" />\n* Anjelika Washington as [[Doctor Mid-Nite#Beth Chapel|Beth Chapel / Doctor Mid-Nite]]: A member of the new Justice Society of America.<ref name=\"Washington\" /><ref name=\"IGNJSAReveal\" />\n* [[Yvette Monreal]] as [[Wildcat (Yolanda Montez)|Yolanda Montez / Wildcat]]: A member of the new Justice Society of America.<ref name=\"MonrealBaker\" /><ref name=\"IGNJSAReveal\" />\n* Christopher James Baker as [[Brainwave (comics)|Henry King / Brainwave]]: A member of the [[Injustice Society]].<ref name=\"MonrealBaker\" /><ref name=\"IGNJSAReveal\" />\n* [[Joy Osmanski]] as [[Tigress (DC Comics)|Paula Brooks / Tigress]]: A member of the Injustice Society who hunts the world's most dangerous humans.<ref name=\"InjusticeSociety\" />\n* [[Neil Hopkins]] as [[Sportsmaster|Lawrence \"Crusher\" Crock / Sportsmaster]]: A member of the Injustice Society who feels all of his targets are part of a game to win.<ref name=\"InjusticeSociety\" />\n* [[Nelson Lee]] as [[Dragon King (DC Comics)|Dr. Ito / Dragon King]]: A member of the Injustice Society and a controversial scientist who hides his face and experiments on himself and his patients.<ref name=\"InjusticeSociety\" /><ref name=\"IGNJSAReveal\" />\n* [[Luke Wilson]] as [[Pat Dugan|Pat Dugan / S.T.R.I.P.E.]]:<br />Courtney's stepfather, the former sidekick to Starman (when he was known as Stripesy), and a mechanic who pilots a 15-foot robot of his own creation.<ref name=\"Wilson\" /> He is a member of the new Justice Society of America.<ref name=\"IGNJSAReveal\" />\n* Cameron Gellman as [[Hourman (Rick Tyler)|Rick Tyler / Hourman]]: A member of the new Justice Society of America.<ref name=\"Gellman\" /><ref name=\"IGNJSAReveal\" />\n* [[Amy Smart]] as Barbara Whitmore: Courtney's mother and wife of Pat Dugan striving to balance her work and home life.<ref name=\"Final4Starring\" />\n* [[Neil Jackson]] as [[Icicle (comics)|Jordan Mahkent / Icicle]]: A member of the Injustice Society.<ref name=\"Final4Starring\" /><ref name=\"IGNJSAReveal\" />\n* Hunter Sansone<ref name=\"Final4Starring\" />\n* Trae Romano as Mike Dugan: Pat Dugan's son and Courtney's stepbrother.<ref name=\"Final4Starring\" />\n\n===Recurring===\n* [[Joel McHale]] as [[Sylvester Pemberton|Sylvester Pemberton / Starman]]: A member of the original Justice Society of America who used an anti-gravity cosmic staff that Courtney finds.<ref name=\"McHale\" />\n* [[Lou Ferrigno, Jr.]] as [[Hourman (Rex Tyler)|Rex Tyler / Hourman]]: A member of the original Justice Society of America, who is \"a master chemist and adrenaline junkie\" with the ability to acquire super-strength for one hour a day.<ref name=\"Ferrigno\" />\n* Brian Stapf as [[Wildcat (Ted Grant)|Ted Grant / Wildcat]]: A member of the original Justice Society of America, who is a former heavyweight boxer.<ref name=\"Stapf\" />\n* [[Henry Thomas]] as [[Charles McNider|Charles McNider / Doctor Mid-Nite]]: A member of the original Justice Society of America, who is a detective and a brilliant and forward-thinking medical pioneer.<ref name=\"Thomas\" />\n\n===Guest===\n* Jake Austin Walker<ref name=\"WalkerDeLacy\" />\n* Meg DeLacy as Cindy Burman: The daughter of Dragon King and the most popular student at Blue Valley High who is determined to follow in her father's footsteps.<ref name=\"WalkerDeLacy\" />\n* Hina Khan as a principal<ref name=\"Khan\" />\n\n==Episodes==\n{{Episode table |background=#12223A |overall= |title= |director= |writer= |airdate= |prodcode= |released=y |episodes=\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 1\n| Title           = Pilot\n| RTitle          = <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BuuwJytAyi9/|title=IT. IS. HAPPENING (And I can't wait for y'all to see who I am \ud83d\ude31)|author=Washington, Anjelika (@anjelikaw)|via=[[Instagram]]|date=March 8, 2019|accessdate=April 3, 2020}}</ref>\n| DirectedBy      = [[Glen Winter]]<ref name=\"Winter\" />\n| WrittenBy       = [[Geoff Johns]]<ref name=\"SeriesOrder\" />\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|5|18}}<ref name=\"NewRelease\"/>\n| ProdCode        = \n| ShortSummary    = \n| LineColor       = 12223A\n}}\n{{^|Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 2\n| Title           = \n| RTitle          = \n| DirectedBy      = \n| WrittenBy       = \n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|5|25}}<ref name=\"FutonCritic\">{{cite web |title=Stargirl \u2013 Listings |url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/showatch/dcs-stargirl/listings/ |website=[[The Futon Critic]] |accessdate=March 10, 2020}}</ref>\n| ProdCode        = \n| ShortSummary    = \n| LineColor       = 12223A\n}}\n{{^|Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 3\n| Title           = \n| RTitle          = \n| DirectedBy      = \n| WrittenBy       = \n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|6|1}}<ref name=\"FutonCritic\" />\n| ProdCode        = \n| ShortSummary    = \n| LineColor       = 12223A\n}}\n{{^|Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 4\n| Title           = \n| RTitle          = \n| DirectedBy      = \n| WrittenBy       = \n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|6|8}}<ref name=\"FutonCritic\" />\n| ProdCode        = \n| ShortSummary    = \n| LineColor       = 12223A\n}}\n{{^|Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 5\n| Title           = \n| RTitle          = \n| DirectedBy      = \n| WrittenBy       = \n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|6|15}}<ref name=\"FutonCritic\" />\n| ProdCode        = \n| ShortSummary    = \n| LineColor       = 12223A\n}}\n{{^|Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 6\n| Title           = \n| RTitle          = \n| DirectedBy      = \n| WrittenBy       = \n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|6|22}}<ref name=\"FutonCritic\" />\n| ProdCode        = \n| ShortSummary    = \n| LineColor       = 12223A\n}}\n{{^|Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 7\n| Title           = \n| RTitle          = \n| DirectedBy      = \n| WrittenBy       = \n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020||}}\n| ProdCode        = \n| ShortSummary    = \n| LineColor       = 12223A\n}}\n{{^|Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 8\n| Title           = \n| RTitle          = \n| DirectedBy      = \n| WrittenBy       = \n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020||}}\n| ProdCode        = \n| ShortSummary    = \n| LineColor       = 12223A\n}}\n{{^|Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 9\n| Title           = \n| RTitle          = \n| DirectedBy      = \n| WrittenBy       = \n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020||}}\n| ProdCode        = \n| ShortSummary    = \n| LineColor       = 12223A\n}}\n{{^|Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 10\n| Title           = \n| RTitle          = \n| DirectedBy      = \n| WrittenBy       = \n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020||}}\n| ProdCode        = \n| ShortSummary    = \n| LineColor       = 12223A\n}}\n{{^|Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 11\n| Title           = \n| RTitle          = \n| DirectedBy      = \n| WrittenBy       = \n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020||}}\n| ProdCode        = \n| ShortSummary    = \n| LineColor       = 12223A\n}}\n{{^|Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 12\n| Title           = \n| RTitle          = \n| DirectedBy      = \n| WrittenBy       = \n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020||}}\n| ProdCode        = \n| ShortSummary    = \n| LineColor       = 12223A\n}}\n{{^|Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 13\n| Title           = \n| RTitle          = \n| DirectedBy      = \n| WrittenBy       = \n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020||}}\n| ProdCode        = \n| ShortSummary    = \n| LineColor       = 12223A\n}}\n}}\n\nAdditional episodes of the first season include:<ref name=\"WGA\" />{{efn|name=Order|Episodes are currently ordered based on the \"credit date\" on the [[Writers Guild of America West]] website.<ref name=\"WGA\">{{Cite web |url=https://directories.wga.org/project/1177235/stargirl/ |title=Stargirl |website=[[Writers Guild of America West]] |access-date=April 3, 2020}}</ref>}} \n\n*\"Brainwave\" written by [[Colleen McGuinness]]\n*\"Brainwave, Jr.\" written by [[James Robinson (writer)|James Dale Robinson]]\n*\"Hourman and Dr. Mid-Nite\" written by Melissa Carter\n*\"Icicle\" written by Colleen McGuinness\n*\"Justice Society Of America\" written by Taylor Streitz\n*\"S.T.R.I.P.E.\" written by Geoff Johns\n*\"Shiv Part One\" written by Evan Ball\n*\"Shiv Part Two\" written by Paula Sevenbergen\n*\"Wildcat\" written by James Dale Robinson\n*\"Stars & S.T.R.I.P.E. Part One\" written by Melissa Carter\n*\"Stars & S.T.R.I.P.E. Part Two\" written by Geoff Johns\n{{notelist}}\n\n==Production==\n===Development===\nOn July 19, 2018, it was announced that [[DC Universe (streaming service)|DC Universe]] had given a series order to ''Stargirl'', consisting of thirteen episodes. The pilot is set to be written by [[Geoff Johns]] who will executive produce alongside [[Greg Berlanti]] and [[Sarah Schechter]]. Production companies involved with the series are Mad Ghost Productions, Berlanti Productions, and [[Warner Bros. Television]]. The series was said to be a \"reimagining\" of [[Courtney Whitmore|Stargirl]].<ref name=\"SeriesOrder\" />\n\n===Writing===\nJohns described ''Stargirl'' as having a similar tone to 1980s films such as ''[[E.T. the Extra-Terrestrial]]'' and ''[[Back to the Future]]''. The start of the series sees the deaths of the original members of the [[Justice Society of America]] (JSA). With the younger generation taking up their mantle, Johns said their \"paths aren't complete. They don't know where they're going to be or what they're going to be. And so, there's all sorts of mistakes they can make and choices they can make, and who knows what their ultimate destiny will be?... It makes for a lot of fun and a lot of unpredictability.\" The members of the [[Injustice Society]] mirrors those on the JSA team, with Johns teasing that just about everyone who has been a member of the Injustice Society in the comics would appear in the series. Speaking to classic JSA members such as [[Alan Scott]] and [[Flash (Jay Garrick)|Jay Garrick]], Johns called them the \"elderly statesmen\" and that they \"are spoken of and they exist in the JSA\" with \"their legacies... felt throughout the show\". There were also \"plans in the future for things\". For the first season, star [[Brec Bassinger]] felt the original [[Charles McNider|Doctor Mid-Nite, Charles McNider]] would have \"a significant role to play\", while Johns added the season would establish the [[Seven Soldiers of Victory]] and the first superhero team before the JSA and explore the history of the Cosmic Staff.<ref name=\"IGNJSAReveal\" />\n\n===Casting===\nIn September 2018, it was announced that [[Brec Bassinger]] had been cast as [[Courtney Whitmore|Courtney Whitmore / Stargirl]].<ref name=\"Bassinger\" /> Johns called the casting of Stargirl a difficult process, auditioning hundreds of actress for the role. On why Bassinger was perfect for the role, Johns said, \"Immediately... I knew she was Courtney. She has the humor, she has the enthusiasm, the energy, the innate optimism, and Brec really embodies who Stargirl is\".<ref name=\"IGNJSAReveal\" /> In November 2018, the following roles were cast: Anjelika Washington as [[Doctor Mid-Nite#Beth Chapel|Beth Chapel / Doctor Mid-Nite]],<ref name=\"Washington\" /><ref name=\"IGNJSAReveal\" /> [[Yvette Monreal]] as [[Wildcat (Yolanda Montez)|Yolanda Montez / Wildcat]], and Christopher James Baker as [[Brainwave (comics)|Henry King / Brainwave]].<ref name=\"MonrealBaker\" /><ref name=\"IGNJSAReveal\" /> The next month, [[Joy Osmanski]] was cast as [[Tigress (DC Comics)|Paula Brooks / Tigress]], [[Neil Hopkins]] was cast as [[Sportsmaster|Lawrence \u201cCrusher\u201d Crock / Sportsmaster]], and [[Nelson Lee]] was cast as [[Dragon King (DC Comics)|Dr. Ito / Dragon King]], members of the [[Injustice Society]].<ref name=\"InjusticeSociety\" /><ref name=\"IGNJSAReveal\" /> In January 2019, [[Luke Wilson]] was cast as [[Pat Dugan|Pat Dugan / S.T.R.I.P.E.]]<ref name=\"Wilson\" /> Cameron Gellman joined the cast as [[Hourman (Rick Tyler)|Rick Tyler / Hourman]] the next month,<ref name=\"Gellman\" /><ref name=\"IGNJSAReveal\" /> along with [[Amy Smart]] as Barbara Whitmore,<ref name=\"Final4Starring\" /> [[Neil Jackson]] as [[Icicle (comics)|Jordan Mahkent / Icicle]],<ref name=\"Final4Starring\" /><ref name=\"IGNJSAReveal\" /> Trae Romano as Mike Dugan, and Hunter Sansone in an undisclosed role rounding out the cast.<ref name=\"Final4Starring\" />\n\nIn December 2018, the following members of the [[Justice Society of America]] were cast, all recurring roles: [[Joel McHale]] as [[Sylvester Pemberton|Sylvester Pemberton / Starman]],<ref name=\"McHale\" /> [[Lou Ferrigno, Jr.]] as [[Hourman (Rex Tyler)|Rex Tyler / Hourman]],<ref name=\"Ferrigno\" /> Brian Stapf as [[Wildcat (Ted Grant)|Ted Grant / Wildcat]],<ref name=\"Stapf\" /> and [[Henry Thomas]] as [[Charles McNider|Charles McNider / Doctor Mid-Nite]].<ref name=\"Thomas\" /> In February 2019, Jake Austin Walker was cast in an undisclosed role and Meg Delacy was cast as Cindy Burman.<ref name=\"WalkerDeLacy\" /> In April 2019, Hina Khan was cast in an undisclosed role said to be a principal.<ref name=\"Khan\" />\n\n===Filming===\nFilming had began by March 14, 2019,<ref name=\"AtlantaFilmingStart\" /> with [[Glen Winter]] directing the pilot.<ref name=\"Winter\" /> Filming occurs throughout the [[Atlanta metropolitan area]], including: [[Marietta, Georgia|Marietta]], [[Virginia\u2013Highland]], [[Duluth, Georgia|Duluth]], [[Lithia Springs, Georgia|Lithia Springs]], [[Dallas, Georgia|Dallas]],<ref name=\"AtlantaFilmingStart\" /> [[Marietta Square]], [[West End, Atlanta|West End]], [[Westlake High School (Georgia)|Westlake High School]], the Atlanta Center for Medical Research,<ref name=\"AtlantaFilming2\" /> Campbell Middle School, [[Paulding County, Georgia|Paulding County]], [[Smyrna, Georgia|Smyrna]], [[Arbor Place]] Mall, [[Vinings, Georgia|Vinings]],<ref name=\"AtlantaFilming3\" /> [[Mableton, Georgia|Mableton]], and [[Douglas County High School (Douglasville, Georgia)|Douglas County High School]].<ref name=\"AtlantaFilming4\" />\n\n===Music===\nIn June 2019, [[Pinar Toprak]] revealed she would be composing for the series.<ref name=\"Toprak\" />\n\n==Release==\n''Stargirl'' is scheduled to begin airing on DC Universe on May 18, 2020.<ref name=\"NewRelease\" /> The series was originally intended to begin airing on May 11, 2020.<ref name=\"OriginalReleaseDate\" /> In November 2019, it was announced that [[The CW]] would broadcast each episode the day after it premieres on the streaming service, with each episode available to stream on The CW's online platforms after its broadcast.<ref name=\"The CW\" /> It will start airing on The CW on May 19, 2020, at 8 pm.<ref name=\"NewRelease\" />\n\n===Marketing===\nOn December 7, 2019, a teaser trailer was released.<ref name=\"FirstTrailer\" />\n\n==Arrowverse==\n{{Main|Crisis on Infinite Earths (Arrowverse)}}\nStargirl and her team were briefly introduced in the [[Arrowverse]] crossover \"[[Crisis on Infinite Earths (Arrowverse)|Crisis on Infinite Earths]]\" in January 2020. ''Stargirl'' is set on a new [[Earth-2 (Arrowverse post-Crisis)|Earth-2]], created during the crossover.<ref name=\"ScreenRantCrisis\" /><ref name=\"ScreenRantCrisis2\" /> Stargirl had previously appeared in three episodes of [[Legends of Tomorrow (season 2)|season two]] of ''[[Legends of Tomorrow]]'', portrayed by [[Sarah Grey]], between October 2016 and February 2017.<ref name=\"LegendsStargirl\" />\n\nRegarding any proper crossovers with the Arrowverse, Johns and Bassinger were keen on the idea. In April 2020, Johns said, \"right now the main concern is making sure that this show is great, that these characters are great, that they have their own stories and they get the proper screen time and the proper episodes to develop on their own. So hopefully in the future we can do something fun, but the first season is all about making sure that ''Stargirl'' is the best show it can possibly be.\" Bassinger added that there had already been preliminary discussion about crossing over with ''[[The Flash (2014 TV series)|The Flash]]'', and she was hopeful to be able to crossover with [[Melissa Benoist]] on ''[[Supergirl (TV series)|Supergirl]]''.<ref name=\"IGNJSAReveal\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"SeriesOrder\">{{cite web |last1=Patten |first1=Dominic |title=Geoff Johns To Write & Produce \u2018Stargirl\u2019 Series For DC Universe \u2013 Comic-Con |url=https://deadline.com/2018/07/geoff-johns-stargirl-tv-series-dc-universe-greg-berlanti-wbtv-comic-con-1202429776/ |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |accessdate=July 19, 2018 |date=July 19, 2018}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"LegendsStargirl\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/legends-tomorrow-legion-doom-season-913953|title=Comic-Con: ''Legends of Tomorrow'' to Tackle Legion of Doom Villain Team In Season 2|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|last=Bucksbaum|first=Sydney|date=July 23, 2016|accessdate=April 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Bassinger\">{{cite web |last1=Boucher |first1=Geoff |title=\u2018Stargirl\u2019 Discovered: Warner Bros Takes Shine To Brec Bassinger As DC Universe Superhero |url=https://deadline.com/2018/09/stargirl-brec-bassinger-dc-universe-series-1202468446/ |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |accessdate=September 20, 2018 |date=September 20, 2018}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Washington\">{{cite web|url=https://comicbook.com/dc/2018/11/02/stargirl-casts-anjelika-washington-in-undisclosed-dc-role/|title='Stargirl' Casts Anjelika Washington in Undisclosed DC Role|last=Burlingame|first=Russ|work=Comicbook.com|date=November 2, 2018|accessdate=November 2, 2018}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"MonrealBaker\">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/11/stargirl-yvette-monreal-christopher-james-baker-set-as-regulars-in-dc-universe-series-1202510976/|title=\u