e Debut|work=Deadline Hollywood|first1=Nellie|last1=Andreeva|first2=Denise|last2=Petski|date=November 21, 2019|accessdate=November 21, 2019}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"FirstTrailer\">{{cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/stargirl-show-teaser-trailer-first-dc-universe/|title=First Stargirl Promo Finally Released By DC Universe|last=Behbakht|first=Andy|website=Screen Rant|date=December 7, 2019|accessdate=April 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"ScreenRantCrisis\">{{cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/crisis-infinite-earths-cameos-arrowverse-crossover/|title=Crisis On Infinite Earths: Every Single Cameo In The Arrowverse Crossover|last=Orquiola|first=John|work=Screen Rant|date=January 16, 2020|accessdate=January 16, 2020|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200116175121/https://screenrant.com/crisis-infinite-earths-cameos-arrowverse-crossover/|archivedate=January 16, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"ScreenRantCrisis2\">{{cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/how-crisis-on-infinite-earths-sets-up-stargirls-tv-show/|title=How Crisis on Infinite Earths Sets Up Stargirl's TV Show|last=Morrison|first=Matt|work=Screen Rant|date=January 17, 2020|accessdate=April 2, 2020|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200226134719/https://screenrant.com/how-crisis-on-infinite-earths-sets-up-stargirls-tv-show/|archivedate=February 26, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"OriginalReleaseDate\">{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2020/tv/news/stargirl-dc-universe-premiere-date-1203524013/|title=\u2018Stargirl\u2019 Sets DC Universe, CW Premiere Date|last=Otterson|first=Joe|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=March 4, 2020|accessdate=March 4, 2020}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"NewRelease\">{{cite web|url=https://tvline.com/2020/03/26/stargirl-premiere-date-change-may-19-cw/|title=Stargirl Premiere Pushed Back a Week|last=Mitovitch|first=Matt Webb|work=[[TV Line]]|date=March 26, 2020|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"IGNJSAReveal\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/stargirl-dc-universe-series-cast-characters-jsa-injustice-society|title=Stargirl: Exclusive First Look at the JSA and Injustice Society|last=Schedeen|first=Jesse|work=[[IGN]]|date=March 31, 2020|accessdate=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|8722888}}\n\n{{Justice Society of America}}\n{{DC Comics TV}}\n{{DC Universe programming}}\n\n<!--[[Category:2020s American drama television series]]\n[[Category:2020s American science fiction television series]]-->\n[[Category:American action television series]]\n[[Category:American adventure television series]]\n[[Category:American fantasy television series]]\n[[Category:American fantasy drama television series]]\n[[Category:DC Universe (streaming service) original programming]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Fantasy drama web series]]\n[[Category:Fantasy web series]]\n[[Category:Television programs based on DC Comics]]\n[[Category:Television series by Warner Bros. Television]]\n[[Category:Television shows filmed in Atlanta]]\n[[Category:Television shows filmed in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in Nebraska]]\n[[Category:Upcoming drama television series]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Upcoming American drama web television series}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = Stargirl\n| image                    = Stargirl TV series.jpeg\n| caption                  = \n| genre                    = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Drama (film and television)|Drama]]\n* [[Superhero fiction|Superhero]]\n}}\n| creator                  = [[Geoff Johns]]\n| based_on                 = {{based on|[[Courtney Whitmore|Stargirl]]|Geoff Johns|Lee Moder}}\n| starring                 = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Brec Bassinger]]\n* Anjelika Washington\n* [[Yvette Monreal]]\n* {{nowrap|Christopher James Baker}}\n* [[Joy Osmanski]]\n* [[Neil Hopkins]]\n* [[Nelson Lee]]\n* [[Luke Wilson]]\n* Cameron Gellman\n* [[Amy Smart]]\n* [[Neil Jackson]]\n* Hunter Sansone\n* Trae Romano\n}}\n| composer                 = [[Pinar Toprak]]\n| country                  = United States\n| language                 = English\n| num_seasons              = \n| num_episodes             = \n| list_episodes            = \n| executive_producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* Geoff Johns\n* [[Greg Berlanti]]\n* [[Sarah Schechter]]\n}}\n| producer                 = \n| cinematography           = \n| editor                   = \n| camera                   = \n| runtime                  = \n| company                  = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Mad Ghost Productions]]\n* [[Berlanti Productions]]\n* [[DC Entertainment]]\n* [[Warner Bros. Television]]\n}}\n| network                  = [[DC Universe (streaming service)|DC Universe]]\n| picture_format           = [[1080i]] ([[High-definition television|HDTV]])\n| audio_format             = \n| first_aired              = <!--{{Start date|2020|5|18}}-->\n| last_aired               = \n| website                  = \n}}\n\n'''''Stargirl''''' is an upcoming American [[Drama (film and television)|drama]] [[web television]] series created by [[Geoff Johns]] that will air on [[DC Universe (streaming service)|DC Universe]]. It is based on the [[DC Comics]] [[superhero]] [[Courtney Whitmore|of the same name]] created by Johns and Lee Moder. The series follows Courtney Whitmore, portrayed by [[Brec Bassinger]], who discovers the cosmic staff and becomes the inspiration for a new generation of superheroes who become the [[Justice Society of America]].\n\nDC Universe ordered the series in July 2018. Bassinger was cast in September 2018, with additional castings for her family members, the Justice Society of America, and the [[Injustice Society]] through February 2019. Filming for the series began by March 2019 in the [[Atlanta metropolitan area]] in Georgia.\n\n''Stargirl'' is set to premiere on May 18, 2020. The series will also air the following day on [[The CW]], as well as be available on The CW's digital platforms. Ahead of the series premiere, characters from the series were featured in the [[Arrowverse]] crossover \"[[Crisis on Infinite Earths (Arrowverse)|Crisis on Infinite Earths]]\", establishing ''Stargirl'' as existing on [[Earth-2 (Arrowverse post-Crisis)|a parallel earth to the Arrowverse series]].\n\n==Premise==\nHigh school sophomore [[Courtney Whitmore]] discovers a powerful cosmic staff, and after learning that her step-father [[Pat Dugan]] used to be a hero sidekick, becomes the inspiration for a new generation of superheroes.<ref name=\"Bassinger\" />\n\n==Cast and characters==\n===Main===\n* [[Brec Bassinger]] as [[Courtney Whitmore|Courtney Whitmore / Stargirl]]:<br />A high school sophomore who discovers a powerful cosmic staff and becomes the hero Stargirl.<ref name=\"Bassinger\" /> She is the leader of the new [[Justice Society of America]].<ref name=\"IGNJSAReveal\" /> Bassinger did not look at the previous portrayals of the character by [[Britt Irvin]] on ''[[Smallville]]'' or [[Sarah Grey]] on ''[[Legends of Tomorrow]]'' because they were depicted as \"older, more mature version[s]\" of Stargirl. Bassinger added the series followed the comic ''[[Stars and S.T.R.I.P.E.]]'' more \"in that she's young, high school, naive, which I wanted to bring that into this version of Stargirl.\"<ref name=\"IGNJSAReveal\" />\n* Anjelika Washington as [[Doctor Mid-Nite#Beth Chapel|Beth Chapel / Doctor Mid-Nite]]: A member of the new Justice Society of America.<ref name=\"Washington\" /><ref name=\"IGNJSAReveal\" />\n* [[Yvette Monreal]] as [[Wildcat (Yolanda Montez)|Yolanda Montez / Wildcat]]: A member of the new Justice Society of America.<ref name=\"MonrealBaker\" /><ref name=\"IGNJSAReveal\" />\n* Christopher James Baker as [[Brainwave (comics)|Henry King / Brainwave]]: A member of the [[Injustice Society]].<ref name=\"MonrealBaker\" /><ref name=\"IGNJSAReveal\" />\n* [[Joy Osmanski]] as [[Tigress (DC Comics)|Paula Brooks / Tigress]]: A member of the Injustice Society who hunts the world's most dangerous humans.<ref name=\"InjusticeSociety\" />\n* [[Neil Hopkins]] as [[Sportsmaster|Lawrence \"Crusher\" Crock / Sportsmaster]]: A member of the Injustice Society who feels all of his targets are part of a game to win.<ref name=\"InjusticeSociety\" />\n* [[Nelson Lee]] as [[Dragon King (DC Comics)|Dr. Ito / Dragon King]]: A member of the Injustice Society and a controversial scientist who hides his face and experiments on himself and his patients.<ref name=\"InjusticeSociety\" /><ref name=\"IGNJSAReveal\" />\n* [[Luke Wilson]] as [[Pat Dugan|Pat Dugan / S.T.R.I.P.E.]]:<br />Courtney's stepfather, the former sidekick to Starman (when he was known as Stripesy), and a mechanic who pilots a 15-foot robot of his own creation.<ref name=\"Wilson\" /> He is a member of the new Justice Society of America.<ref name=\"IGNJSAReveal\" />\n* Cameron Gellman as [[Hourman (Rick Tyler)|Rick Tyler / Hourman]]: A member of the new Justice Society of America.<ref name=\"Gellman\" /><ref name=\"IGNJSAReveal\" />\n* [[Amy Smart]] as Barbara Whitmore: Courtney's mother and wife of Pat Dugan striving to balance her work and home life.<ref name=\"Final4Starring\" />\n* [[Neil Jackson]] as [[Icicle (comics)|Jordan Mahkent / Icicle]]: A member of the Injustice Society.<ref name=\"Final4Starring\" /><ref name=\"IGNJSAReveal\" />\n* Hunter Sansone<ref name=\"Final4Starring\" />\n* Trae Romano as Mike Dugan: Pat Dugan's son and Courtney's stepbrother.<ref name=\"Final4Starring\" />\n\n===Recurring===\n* [[Joel McHale]] as [[Sylvester Pemberton|Sylvester Pemberton / Starman]]: A member of the original Justice Society of America who used an anti-gravity cosmic staff that Courtney finds.<ref name=\"McHale\" />\n* [[Lou Ferrigno, Jr.]] as [[Hourman (Rex Tyler)|Rex Tyler / Hourman]]: A member of the original Justice Society of America, who is \"a master chemist and adrenaline junkie\" with the ability to acquire super-strength for one hour a day.<ref name=\"Ferrigno\" />\n* Brian Stapf as [[Wildcat (Ted Grant)|Ted Grant / Wildcat]]: A member of the original Justice Society of America, who is a former heavyweight boxer.<ref name=\"Stapf\" />\n* [[Henry Thomas]] as [[Charles McNider|Charles McNider / Doctor Mid-Nite]]: A member of the original Justice Society of America, who is a detective and a brilliant and forward-thinking medical pioneer.<ref name=\"Thomas\" />\n\n===Guest===\n* Jake Austin Walker<ref name=\"WalkerDeLacy\" />\n* Meg DeLacy as Cindy Burman: The daughter of Dragon King and the most popular student at Blue Valley High who is determined to follow in her father's footsteps.<ref name=\"WalkerDeLacy\" />\n* Hina Khan as a principal<ref name=\"Khan\" />\n\n==Episodes==\n{{Episode table |background=#12223A |overall= |title= |director= |writer= |airdate= |prodcode= |released=y |episodes=\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 1\n| Title           = Pilot\n| RTitle          = <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BuuwJytAyi9/|title=IT. IS. HAPPENING (And I can't wait for y'all to see who I am \ud83d\ude31)|author=Washington, Anjelika (@anjelikaw)|via=[[Instagram]]|date=March 8, 2019|accessdate=April 3, 2020}}</ref>\n| DirectedBy      = [[Glen Winter]]<ref name=\"Winter\" />\n| WrittenBy       = [[Geoff Johns]]<ref name=\"SeriesOrder\" />\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|5|18}}<ref name=\"NewRelease\"/>\n| ProdCode        = \n| ShortSummary    = \n| LineColor       = 12223A\n}}\n{{^|Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 2\n| Title           = \n| RTitle          = \n| DirectedBy      = \n| WrittenBy       = \n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|5|25}}<ref name=\"FutonCritic\">{{cite web |title=Stargirl \u2013 Listings |url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/showatch/dcs-stargirl/listings/ |website=[[The Futon Critic]] |accessdate=March 10, 2020}}</ref>\n| ProdCode        = \n| ShortSummary    = \n| LineColor       = 12223A\n}}\n{{^|Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 3\n| Title           = \n| RTitle          = \n| DirectedBy      = \n| WrittenBy       = \n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|6|1}}<ref name=\"FutonCritic\" />\n| ProdCode        = \n| ShortSummary    = \n| LineColor       = 12223A\n}}\n{{^|Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 4\n| Title           = \n| RTitle          = \n| DirectedBy      = \n| WrittenBy       = \n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|6|8}}<ref name=\"FutonCritic\" />\n| ProdCode        = \n| ShortSummary    = \n| LineColor       = 12223A\n}}\n{{^|Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 5\n| Title           = \n| RTitle          = \n| DirectedBy      = \n| WrittenBy       = \n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|6|15}}<ref name=\"FutonCritic\" />\n| ProdCode        = \n| ShortSummary    = \n| LineColor       = 12223A\n}}\n{{^|Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 6\n| Title           = \n| RTitle          = \n| DirectedBy      = \n| WrittenBy       = \n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|6|22}}<ref name=\"FutonCritic\" />\n| ProdCode        = \n| ShortSummary    = \n| LineColor       = 12223A\n}}\n{{^|Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 7\n| Title           = \n| RTitle          = \n| DirectedBy      = \n| WrittenBy       = \n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020||}}\n| ProdCode        = \n| ShortSummary    = \n| LineColor       = 12223A\n}}\n{{^|Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 8\n| Title           = \n| RTitle          = \n| DirectedBy      = \n| WrittenBy       = \n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020||}}\n| ProdCode        = \n| ShortSummary    = \n| LineColor       = 12223A\n}}\n{{^|Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 9\n| Title           = \n| RTitle          = \n| DirectedBy      = \n| WrittenBy       = \n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020||}}\n| ProdCode        = \n| ShortSummary    = \n| LineColor       = 12223A\n}}\n{{^|Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 10\n| Title           = \n| RTitle          = \n| DirectedBy      = \n| WrittenBy       = \n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020||}}\n| ProdCode        = \n| ShortSummary    = \n| LineColor       = 12223A\n}}\n{{^|Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 11\n| Title           = \n| RTitle          = \n| DirectedBy      = \n| WrittenBy       = \n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020||}}\n| ProdCode        = \n| ShortSummary    = \n| LineColor       = 12223A\n}}\n{{^|Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 12\n| Title           = \n| RTitle          = \n| DirectedBy      = \n| WrittenBy       = \n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020||}}\n| ProdCode        = \n| ShortSummary    = \n| LineColor       = 12223A\n}}\n{{^|Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 13\n| Title           = \n| RTitle          = \n| DirectedBy      = \n| WrittenBy       = \n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020||}}\n| ProdCode        = \n| ShortSummary    = \n| LineColor       = 12223A\n}}\n}}\n\nEpisodes of the first season include:<ref name=\"WGA\" />{{efn|name=Order|Episodes are currently ordered based on the \"credit date\" on the [[Writers Guild of America West]] website.<ref name=\"WGA\">{{Cite web |url=https://directories.wga.org/project/1177235/stargirl/ |title=Stargirl |website=[[Writers Guild of America West]] |access-date=April 3, 2020}}</ref>}} \n\n*\"Brainwave\" written by Colleen McGuinness\n*\"Brainwave, Jr.\" written by James Dale Robinson\n*\"Hourman and Dr. Mid-Nite\" written by Melissa Carter\n*\"Icicle\" written by Colleen McGuinness\n*\"Justice Society Of America\" written by Taylor Streitz\n*\"S.T.R.I.P.E.\" written by Geoff Johns\n*\"Shiv Part One\" written by Evan Ball\n*\"Shiv Part Two\" written by Paula Sevenbergen\n*\"Wildcat\" written by James Dale Robinson\n*\"Stars & S.T.R.I.P.E. Part One\" written by Melissa Carter\n*\"Stars & S.T.R.I.P.E. Part Two\" written by Geoff Johns\n{{notelist}}\n\n==Production==\n===Development===\nOn July 19, 2018, it was announced that [[DC Universe (streaming service)|DC Universe]] had given a series order to ''Stargirl'', consisting of thirteen episodes. The pilot is set to be written by [[Geoff Johns]] who will executive produce alongside [[Greg Berlanti]] and [[Sarah Schechter]]. Production companies involved with the series are Mad Ghost Productions, Berlanti Productions, and [[Warner Bros. Television]]. The series was said to be a \"reimagining\" of [[Courtney Whitmore|Stargirl]].<ref name=\"SeriesOrder\" />\n\n===Writing===\nJohns described ''Stargirl'' as having a similar tone to 1980s films such as ''[[E.T. the Extra-Terrestrial]]'' and ''[[Back to the Future]]''. The start of the series sees the deaths of the original members of the [[Justice Society of America]] (JSA). With the younger generation taking up their mantle, Johns said their \"paths aren't complete. They don't know where they're going to be or what they're going to be. And so, there's all sorts of mistakes they can make and choices they can make, and who knows what their ultimate destiny will be?... It makes for a lot of fun and a lot of unpredictability.\" The members of the [[Injustice Society]] mirrors those on the JSA team, with Johns teasing that just about everyone who has been a member of the Injustice Society in the comics would appear in the series. Speaking to classic JSA members such as [[Alan Scott]] and [[Flash (Jay Garrick)|Jay Garrick]], Johns called them the \"elderly statesmen\" and that they \"are spoken of and they exist in the JSA\" with \"their legacies... felt throughout the show\". There were also \"plans in the future for things\". For the first season, star [[Brec Bassinger]] felt the original [[Charles McNider|Doctor Mid-Nite, Charles McNider]] would have \"a significant role to play\", while Johns added the season would establish the [[Seven Soldiers of Victory]] and the first superhero team before the JSA and explore the history of the Cosmic Staff.<ref name=\"IGNJSAReveal\" />\n\n===Casting===\nIn September 2018, it was announced that [[Brec Bassinger]] had been cast as [[Courtney Whitmore|Courtney Whitmore / Stargirl]].<ref name=\"Bassinger\" /> Johns called the casting of Stargirl a difficult process, auditioning hundreds of actress for the role. On why Bassinger was perfect for the role, Johns said, \"Immediately... I knew she was Courtney. She has the humor, she has the enthusiasm, the energy, the innate optimism, and Brec really embodies who Stargirl is\".<ref name=\"IGNJSAReveal\" /> In November 2018, the following roles were cast: Anjelika Washington as [[Doctor Mid-Nite#Beth Chapel|Beth Chapel / Doctor Mid-Nite]],<ref name=\"Washington\" /><ref name=\"IGNJSAReveal\" /> [[Yvette Monreal]] as [[Wildcat (Yolanda Montez)|Yolanda Montez / Wildcat]], and Christopher James Baker as [[Brainwave (comics)|Henry King / Brainwave]].<ref name=\"MonrealBaker\" /><ref name=\"IGNJSAReveal\" /> The next month, [[Joy Osmanski]] was cast as [[Tigress (DC Comics)|Paula Brooks / Tigress]], [[Neil Hopkins]] was cast as [[Sportsmaster|Lawrence \u201cCrusher\u201d Crock / Sportsmaster]], and [[Nelson Lee]] was cast as [[Dragon King (DC Comics)|Dr. Ito / Dragon King]], members of the [[Injustice Society]].<ref name=\"InjusticeSociety\" /><ref name=\"IGNJSAReveal\" /> In January 2019, [[Luke Wilson]] was cast as [[Pat Dugan|Pat Dugan / S.T.R.I.P.E.]]<ref name=\"Wilson\" /> Cameron Gellman joined the cast as [[Hourman (Rick Tyler)|Rick Tyler / Hourman]] the next month,<ref name=\"Gellman\" /><ref name=\"IGNJSAReveal\" /> along with [[Amy Smart]] as Barbara Whitmore,<ref name=\"Final4Starring\" /> [[Neil Jackson]] as [[Icicle (comics)|Jordan Mahkent / Icicle]],<ref name=\"Final4Starring\" /><ref name=\"IGNJSAReveal\" /> Trae Romano as Mike Dugan, and Hunter Sansone in an undisclosed role rounding out the cast.<ref name=\"Final4Starring\" />\n\nIn December 2018, the following members of the [[Justice Society of America]] were cast, all recurring roles: [[Joel McHale]] as [[Sylvester Pemberton|Sylvester Pemberton / Starman]],<ref name=\"McHale\" /> [[Lou Ferrigno, Jr.]] as [[Hourman (Rex Tyler)|Rex Tyler / Hourman]],<ref name=\"Ferrigno\" /> Brian Stapf as [[Wildcat (Ted Grant)|Ted Grant / Wildcat]],<ref name=\"Stapf\" /> and [[Henry Thomas]] as [[Charles McNider|Charles McNider / Doctor Mid-Nite]].<ref name=\"Thomas\" /> In February 2019, Jake Austin Walker was cast in an undisclosed role and Meg Delacy was cast as Cindy Burman.<ref name=\"WalkerDeLacy\" /> In April 2019, Hina Khan was cast in an undisclosed role said to be a principal.<ref name=\"Khan\" />\n\n===Filming===\nFilming had began by March 14, 2019,<ref name=\"AtlantaFilmingStart\" /> with [[Glen Winter]] directing the pilot.<ref name=\"Winter\" /> Filming occurs throughout the [[Atlanta metropolitan area]], including: [[Marietta, Georgia|Marietta]], [[Virginia\u2013Highland]], [[Duluth, Georgia|Duluth]], [[Lithia Springs, Georgia|Lithia Springs]], [[Dallas, Georgia|Dallas]],<ref name=\"AtlantaFilmingStart\" /> [[Marietta Square]], [[West End, Atlanta|West End]], [[Westlake High School (Georgia)|Westlake High School]], the Atlanta Center for Medical Research,<ref name=\"AtlantaFilming2\" /> Campbell Middle School, [[Paulding County, Georgia|Paulding County]], [[Smyrna, Georgia|Smyrna]], [[Arbor Place]] Mall, [[Vinings, Georgia|Vinings]],<ref name=\"AtlantaFilming3\" /> [[Mableton, Georgia|Mableton]], and [[Douglas County High School (Douglasville, Georgia)|Douglas County High School]].<ref name=\"AtlantaFilming4\" />\n\n===Music===\nIn June 2019, [[Pinar Toprak]] revealed she would be composing for the series.<ref name=\"Toprak\" />\n\n==Release==\n''Stargirl'' is scheduled to begin airing on DC Universe on May 18, 2020.<ref name=\"NewRelease\" /> The series was originally intended to begin airing on May 11, 2020.<ref name=\"OriginalReleaseDate\" /> In November 2019, it was announced that [[The CW]] would broadcast each episode the day after it premieres on the streaming service, with each episode available to stream on The CW's online platforms after its broadcast.<ref name=\"The CW\" /> It will start airing on The CW on May 19, 2020, at 8 pm.<ref name=\"NewRelease\" />\n\n===Marketing===\nOn December 7, 2019, a teaser trailer was released.<ref name=\"FirstTrailer\" />\n\n==Arrowverse==\n{{Main|Crisis on Infinite Earths (Arrowverse)}}\nStargirl and her team were briefly introduced in the [[Arrowverse]] crossover \"[[Crisis on Infinite Earths (Arrowverse)|Crisis on Infinite Earths]]\" in January 2020. ''Stargirl'' is set on a new [[Earth-2 (Arrowverse post-Crisis)|Earth-2]], created during the crossover.<ref name=\"ScreenRantCrisis\" /><ref name=\"ScreenRantCrisis2\" /> Stargirl had previously appeared in three episodes of [[Legends of Tomorrow (season 2)|season two]] of ''[[Legends of Tomorrow]]'', portrayed by [[Sarah Grey]], between October 2016 and February 2017.<ref name=\"LegendsStargirl\" />\n\nRegarding any proper crossovers with the Arrowverse, Johns and Bassinger were keen on the idea. In April 2020, Johns said, \"right now the main concern is making sure that this show is great, that these characters are great, that they have their own stories and they get the proper screen time and the proper episodes to develop on their own. So hopefully in the future we can do something fun, but the first season is all about making sure that ''Stargirl'' is the best show it can possibly be.\" Bassinger added that there had already been preliminary discussion about crossing over with ''[[The Flash (2014 TV series)|The Flash]]'', and she was hopeful to be able to crossover with [[Melissa Benoist]] on ''[[Supergirl (TV series)|Supergirl]]''.<ref name=\"IGNJSAReveal\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"SeriesOrder\">{{cite web |last1=Patten |first1=Dominic |title=Geoff Johns To Write & Produce \u2018Stargirl\u2019 Series For DC Universe \u2013 Comic-Con |url=https://deadline.com/2018/07/geoff-johns-stargirl-tv-series-dc-universe-greg-berlanti-wbtv-comic-con-1202429776/ |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |accessdate=July 19, 2018 |date=July 19, 2018}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"LegendsStargirl\">{{cite web|url=http:/